Biswa, was the dark horse of the contest. I had a winner in mind until the morning I I went to select  my "winner" and saw the entry from Biswa.  I was very impressed, unlike the other, entries he provides an application dashboard, rather than a static image of a web theme, a risky expectation to set.  I recognized his eagerness to challenge himself and his enthusiasm for coding. 
Although time zones can be a challenge, he always made the effort to communicate with me. He would explain his process so I would understand his method, this was helpful when I couldn't see visible progress. I would review our chat to see that he would be focused on the backend coding first, necessary to make the front end design function.  It's been my experience in past projects, I would see my content and believe "wow this gal great" however when it came to getting the function to work with the design, it either took twice as long or just never happened. 
Biswa, on the other hand,  put function before form, in other words, like building a solid house, he spent the time laying the foundation, framing the house, fitting it out with the correct code, reviewing the function with me , helping me understand the nuances and about 7 days into the project  I logged in and started seeing my content in action (not as an image).  At that point, my mind confirmed what my intuition had already known. Biswa is excellent, he's committed long-term to his work and clients. I highly recommend him.

dyrjoh did an unbelievable job on my animated explainer video.  I knew him from Norwegian translations he did for me.  His advanced translation skills and professionalism really came through on many accounts in this way, so when I knew I needed some animation work, I remembered he had written in his profile that animation was his real passion.  This is always important for me when I choose to work with people - passion.

So I contacted him about my project.  I gave him a fairly detailed story-board of what I wanted.  Likely between 90 and 120 seconds.  He exceeded my expectations.  He hit all my important ideas on the nose and took other ideas and made them more elegant.  He is also very good in dealing with feedback.  In the end it was going to be my video, so I know I wanted to give good constructive comments back to make as good a production as possible, and dyrjoh wants to accomplish this with you.  So I would encourage you to have good, fair feedback for him,  

With all this said, I wanted to create a quality animation for a fair price.  Too much these days, people want something amazing or unlimited revisions for next to no money.   This is unreasonable and you should know this going in.  If you want a top-quality animation for a fair price from a professional with great skills and an ability to edit and really punch through on the important points you need to hit, you need to have a conversation with dyrjoh about your project.

I hired the freelancer to do a PPC project for a client. The project was completed within the time frame that the freelancer said, and the work seemed to be completed well. 

There were some areas that are worth mentioning in the review for other's to look out for.

1. I requested a freelancer only from the US. 
Even though the freelancer said he was based in Chicago, and was happy to jump on a phone call. The command of the English language wasn't there. Also, the sense of urgency was only to be paid quickly and to set expectations in his favor.

2. Specific instructions on the PPC campaign.
I had to go back and forth in a chat conversation with this freelancer about a set of specific instructions. It was one of those "I know better about this topic, so I'm going to to do it like this." type of conversations. It was a waste of time, but he did compromise to my instructions eventually.

3. The communication was poor.
The freelancer called me to release his money when I hadn't even made it into my office yet. The phone/communication etiquette needs a lot of work. Ask before calling, set up a time, etc.

Over all, the idea of my hiring a local specialists didn't work out. I still got a foreigner that was difficult to work with.

Dayalmodal3322 (D) provided the winning submission to my contest.  I would say the quality of the winning logo is above average, but only because I received numerous submissions that were terrible.  The logo provided looks like stock art, but then again, so did most of the others.  I priced the contest prize on the lower end, because I was afraid of overpaying for poor quality entries, and I mostly got what I expected.  

On to why I give D negative marks on communication and professionalism: every communication I received from D was insistent and relentless.  D was relatively quick with replies, but in the event I was unable to reply quickly, I could count on a bombardment of messages.  Then, once D was picked as the winner, there were more messages seeking a favorable review.  I informed D that I would leave a review when I could.  When I could was not soon enough for D, because I received more messages about the review.  

To sum up: I received about the same quality logo I have received in the past on Fiverr, but in this case paid more money.  I guaranteed the contest, so I was forced to go with the least bad option, which was submitted by a designer with no respect for my time.  It was a learning experience, and I'm not certain I will use the contest format again in the future.

Sadly, some of the poorest work I have ever seen in my professional career since working in this industry. I am a computer science graduate, so I am fully aware of the requirements for web design. As a company MobiWeb do come across as a professional outfit, however under-the-hood things are very different. We paid this company ~$10K and the delivery was nothing but a disappointment (unfinished dev, no QA and major functionality left non-operational). 

In truth, MobiWeb can offer basic CSS templates, simple designs and installations of CRM's. However, anything more sophisticated is problematic and out of their knowledge depth. Our CSS was reasonable, but the product never worked and was delivered full of bugs.

In the end these projects are about trust, communication and good quality of work. Mobiweb lied and failed to deliver on their promises. Some of their work was so bad that we have recently removed over 3000 lines of code from a FabricJS library written by them. It is obvious now that they are not strong in this particularly area, but during initial consultation they agreed that they could do the job. 

I would recommend Mobiweb only for simple projects (HTML/CSS) and that for anything more complicated seek alternatives.

Oleksandra responded the next day, one of perhaps 10-15 artists. On checking her portfolio, we decided her style was perfect for our $500 budget. We were looking for a one week turnaround, and admittedly I was a little apprehensive about her being half way around the work…in the Ukraine.

Bottom line? We look forward to working with Oleksandra in the future, and in fact relying on her services—regularly—for new projects. She demonstrated a complete mastery of her Photoshop and 3D rendering techniques, in addition to being an ace designer (check out her portfolio!).

Tl;dr: Michael deserves a ten star review for his professionalism and in-depth knowledge in online marketing, his business and client oriented attitude and his joyful and punctual working manner.

Michael helped us for a considerable amount of time in a few ways. 

Online marketing: We collaborated a LOT on working out the marketing strategy for a new company and Michael pulled it off to make it a profitable business. We worked and tested very carefully on (re-)marketing through Facebook and Google until we found a winning mix. He has been very flexibel and approachable along the way. We achieved good results, mostly thanks to his prudent way of testing different approaches.

Business orientation: The company we were setting up was sin its infancies and we had not thought about many things. Michael indicated in brainstorm sessions several opportunities worth pursuing. This is truly a unique and valuable trait of this person. Not working FOR the client but working WITH the client.

Working manner: The working manner with Michael has been joyful throughout. We worked hard, yes, but there was always room for a joke or two. Or five. The laughter did not influence the working ethic, professionality or punctuality negatively. On the contrary, it felt very much like teamwork.

In all, I would, and will, definitely hire Michael again. He is an example for freelancers with his profession. Five stars is not enough!
